Amidst the COVID 19 pandemic, the Nigeria Customs Service, Federal Operations Unit (FOU) Zone ‘B’ has arrested four persons in connection with smuggled contraband goods worth N176,974,600 Duty Paid Value (DPV). The smuggled items, according to the Public Relations Officer (PRO) of the zone, Assistant Superintendent of Customs 1(ASC1) Abubakar Usman, included 493 (50Kg) bags of foreign parboiled rice, 284 bundles of Shadda brocades, 63 bales of textile materials as well as 213 bags of foreign fertilisers. ASC1 Usman who addressed newsmen on the seized items shortly after taking newsmen round the trucks containing the seized items, said the arrested suspects are undergoing interrogation and will be prosecuted accordingly upon completion of investigation. The PRO disclosed that the smuggled bags of rice were concealed in trucks carrying bags of maize, beans, water melons and tiger nuts. The seizures, according to him, were made within three days in border towns of Kebbi, Katsina as well as the hinterlands of Zamfara States. He said the seized containerised vehicle had in it 249 bags of smuggled rise concealed in bags of beans. Also, another truck carrying 125 bags of rice concealed in bags of maize, canter carrying 119 bags of smuggled rice sandwiched between water melon, truck carrying 63 bales of textiles and 284 bundles of Shadda brocade and 213 bags of fertilizer were seized. ASC1 Usman also explained that the seizures were as a result of operations carried out by officers and men of the zone following a tip off. He appealed to the public to report any suspicious movement of trucks and persons who are bent on sabotaging the economy through their smuggling activities.